Anonymous Sun 06 May 2018 03:42:23 No.15591276 Report
Quoted By: >>15591493
>>15591032
Whew, ok let's see...


The chart would show things like those classic "not a furry > somewhat furry > furry > wtf r u doin" charts, but it would show compatability of pregnancy chances.
The chances of pregnancy are greater the closer the sections are to each other.

Now to go into things like "well, what would the child even look like?," let's use the "mother is the species, the father is the traits" argument, for now.
Let's say the father is human with blonde hair (to make it interesting) and hazel eyes, and the anthro is a female wolf with grey fur and amber eyes.
>wow so original blokfort
The child would be a wolf, but let's say the fur coloring would match the hair color of the human. Of course, things like the general use of past ancestor's genes can come into play.

>so, the child would be a wolf, with blonde fur and hazel eyes?
Eeeeh, not quite.
It depends on how strong the genes from the respective parents are.
Just like having a ginger kid is possible when one parent has black hair and the other is ginger, it's possible to have grey fur yet the father has blonde hair.
The same kind of thinking can apply to things like diseases and medical disabilities as well, though there are still a lot of really odd cases where neither parent will have the gene, yet the child does.
Fucking biology with millions of cells and growth patterns make pretty much anything possible, but for the sake of simplicity, you can look at the two parents and say "these traits are possible, which some traits more possible than others"


How's that?
